================================================================================
FAQ GENERATION FLOW - BUILD GUIDE
Steps 1 to 3: Prompt, Parse, Excel
================================================================================


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SECTION 1 - ADDING THE AI BUILDER PROMPT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

BEFORE YOU START
Create the custom prompt in AI Builder first, then come back to wire it in.

  1a. Go to make.powerapps.com
  1b. Navigate to AI Builder > Prompts > New prompt
  1c. Name it: FAQ Generator
  1d. Paste the full prompt text from the PROMPT section at the bottom of
      this file
  1e. Add two inputs:
        - Name: documentName    Type: Text
        - Name: documentFile    Type: File
  1f. Save the prompt


REPLACE COMPOSE IN THE WORD BRANCH (True branch)

  Your current structure:
    Convert Word Document to PDF
    > Compose                         <-- replace this
    > Set varResponseJSON Word

  Steps:
  1. Delete the existing Compose action in the Word branch
  2. In its place, add action: AI Builder > Create text with GPT
     (search for "Run a prompt" or "Create text using a prompt")
  3. Select your saved prompt: FAQ Generator
  4. Wire the inputs:
       - documentName = FileNameWithExtension
         (from trigger: triggerOutputs()?['body/{FilenameWithExtension}'])
       - documentFile = File content from Convert Word Document to PDF
         (use the 'File content' output of the conversion action)
  5. Leave Set varResponseJSON Word in place - update its value in step below


REPLACE COMPOSE IN THE PDF BRANCH (False branch)

  Your current structure:
    Get file content 1
    > Compose 1                       <-- replace this
    > Set varResponseJSON PDF

  Steps:
  1. Delete Compose 1 in the PDF branch
  2. Add action: AI Builder > Create text with GPT
  3. Select prompt: FAQ Generator
  4. Wire the inputs:
       - documentName = FileNameWithExtension
         (same trigger expression as above)
       - documentFile = File content from Get file content 1
         (use the 'File content' output of that action)
  5. Leave Set varResponseJSON PDF in place - update below


UPDATE BOTH SET VARIABLE ACTIONS

  In both branches, update the Set varResponseJSON action value to:

    outputs('Create_text_with_GPT')?['body/predictionOutput/text']

  NOTE: The exact action name in the expression depends on what Power Automate
  auto-names your AI Builder action. If you have two AI Builder actions,
  they will be named differently - check the action name in the expression
  builder and match it exactly.

  Typical output path for AI Builder custom prompts:
    outputs('ACTION_NAME')?['body/predictionOutput/text']


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SECTION 2 - CLEANING AND PARSING THE JSON RESPONSE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Add these two actions AFTER the Condition block (after both branches merge),
using the varResponseJSON variable which now holds the AI Builder output.


STEP 2.1 - COMPOSE: CLEAN THE RESPONSE

  Action: Data Operations > Compose
  Name it: Compose_CleanJSON

  Expression value (paste into expression editor):
    trim(replace(replace(variables('varResponseJSON'),concat('`','`','`','json'),''),concat('`','`','`'),''))

  What this does: strips any markdown code fences the model may have wrapped
  around the JSON before you try to parse it. Without this, Parse JSON fails.

  NOTE: Backtick characters cannot be typed directly in the Power Automate
  expression editor. The concat approach above constructs them safely.
  Alternatively paste this version if your editor accepts backticks directly:
    trim(replace(replace(variables('varResponseJSON'),'```json',''),'```',''))


STEP 2.2 - PARSE JSON

  Action: Data Operations > Parse JSON
  Name it: Parse_FAQ_JSON

  Content: outputs('Compose_CleanJSON')

  Schema (paste this in full):

  {
    "type": "array",
    "items": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "category": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "question": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "expectedAnswer": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "confidence": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "category",
        "question",
        "expectedAnswer",
        "confidence"
      ]
    }
  }

  TIP: If the AI Builder response is empty or malformed, Parse JSON will fail.
  Wrap this action (and everything after it) in a Scope action so you can
  configure error handling. Set a parallel branch with "Configure run after >
  Has failed" to update a status column or send an alert email.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SECTION 3 - GENERATING THE EXCEL FILE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

STEP 3.1 - GET THE EXCEL TEMPLATE

  Action: SharePoint > Get file content
  Name it: Get_Excel_Template

  Site Address: [your SharePoint site]
  File Identifier: /Frequently Asked Questions/Templates/FAQ_Template.xlsx

  NOTE: Use the full relative path from the root of the site, not from a
  library. Adjust to match your actual folder structure.


STEP 3.2 - CREATE THE OUTPUT EXCEL FILE

  Action: SharePoint > Create file
  Name it: Create_FAQ_Excel

  Site Address: [your SharePoint site]

  Folder Path: /Frequently Asked Questions/Output
  (This is the destination folder only - do not include the filename here)

  If routing by Business Unit, use this expression in the Folder Path field:
    concat('/FAQ Outputs/', triggerBody()?['{BusinessUnit}'])

  File Name (expression - paste into expression editor):
    concat(
      replace(
        replace(
          triggerOutputs()?['body/{FilenameWithExtension}'],
          '.pdf',
          ''
        ),
        '.docx',
        ''
      ),
      '_FAQs_',
      formatDateTime(utcNow(), 'yyyy-MM-dd'),
      '.xlsx'
    )

  NOTE: Both .pdf and .docx extensions are stripped. The Word branch converts
  to PDF inside the flow but the trigger filename is still the original .docx,
  so both must be handled.

  File Content: outputs('Get_Excel_Template')?['body']

  This copies your formatted template (with headers, table, and conditional
  formatting intact) and saves it as a new named file.


STEP 3.3 - POPULATE THE EXCEL TABLE

  Action: Control > Apply to each
  Input: body('Parse_FAQ_JSON')

  Inside the loop, add:
  Action: Excel Online (Business) > Add a row into a table

    Location: [your SharePoint site URL]
    Document Library: [your document library name]
    File: outputs('Create_FAQ_Excel')?['body/Id']
    Table: FAQTable    <-- must match the exact table name in your template

    Column mappings:
      Category        = items()?['category']
      Question        = items()?['question']
      ExpectedAnswer  = items()?['expectedAnswer']
      Confidence      = items()?['confidence']

  IMPORTANT: The File field in the Excel action requires the SharePoint
  file ID returned by the Create file action, not a path. Use the expression
  above to reference it. If you hard-code a path here it will break.

  IMPORTANT: Your Excel table must be a proper formatted Table object
  (Insert > Table in Excel), not just a header row. If it is not a Table,
  the "Add a row" action will not find it. Verify the table is named
  FAQTable in Excel under Table Design > Table Name.


STEP 3.4 - GET A SHARING LINK

  Action: SharePoint > Create sharing link for a file or folder
  Name it: Get_Sharing_Link

  Site Address: [your SharePoint site]
  Library name: [your document library]
  Item Id: outputs('Create_FAQ_Excel')?['body/ItemId']
  Link type: Organization view

  This generates a direct link to the completed Excel file for the email.


STEP 3.5 - SEND EMAIL NOTIFICATION

  Action: Office 365 Outlook > Send an email (V2)

  To:
    triggerOutputs()?['body/Editor/Email']

    NOTE: This gets the email of the person who uploaded the file from the
    trigger metadata. Test this field first - if it returns empty, fall back
    to: triggerOutputs()?['body/Author/Email']

  Subject:
    concat('Your FAQ document is ready - ',
    triggerOutputs()?['body/{FilenameWithExtension}'])

  Body - set Is HTML to Yes in the email action, then paste this expression:
    concat(
      '<p>Hi,</p>',
      '<p>Your FAQ set has been generated and is ready for review.</p>',
      '<p><strong>Document processed:</strong> ',
      triggerOutputs()?['body/{FilenameWithExtension}'],
      '</p>',
      '<p><a href="',
      outputs('Get_Sharing_Link')?['body/sharingLink/webUrl'],
      '">Open your FAQ file</a></p>',
      '<p>Any entries highlighted in red are low confidence and should be ',
      'reviewed before use in agent training or evaluation.</p>',
      '<p>This file was generated automatically.</p>'
    )

  NOTE: HTML tags are used here instead of \n sequences. Power Automate does
  not interpret \n as line breaks inside string expressions - it outputs the
  literal characters \n. Set Is HTML to Yes on the email action.


